    "rationale": "Current weights (0.4/0.4/0.1/0.1) already yield strong stability: test mean absolute delta is 0.0206 and validation mean absolute delta is 0.0225, both well within the 0.05 tolerance. The one problematic pair is 689\u21941560, which shows the largest deviations (validation delta \u22120.058, test delta +0.047). Examining its features: pass_score shifts substantially across splits (train 0.605, val 0.486, test 0.715) while image_similarity is thin (only 1\u20134 common image dates in val/test vs 101 in train), making image_similarity noisy for low-overlap pairs. Slightly increasing pass_score weight to 0.45 and reducing image_similarity to 0.35 favors the more consistently populated feature across splits. purpose_match and temperature_similarity remain at 0.10 each \u2014 both are present and stable across all pairs, and their current contribution is appropriate given they act as secondary regularizers. This is a conservative nudge rather than a large rebalancing, preserving the already-good baseline stability.",
    "expected_effect": "Modest reduction in test mean absolute delta for pairs with sparse image overlap (especially 689\u21941560 and 689\u21941994 where common_image_dates drop to 1\u20139 in val/test). Pass_score, computed from full pass-date counts (7\u201331 dates), remains better populated and more reliable in short windows. Overall mean absolute delta expected to remain near or below 0.020 on test, with marginal improvement on the outlier pair.",
    "risks": [
      "689\u21941560 test delta is already 0.047, near the 0.05 tolerance; if pass_score itself becomes noisy in future splits with fewer common pass dates, the higher pass_score weight could amplify rather than reduce drift.",
      "Reducing image_similarity weight may slightly hurt pairs like 2546\u21941560 where image data is abundant (21\u2013286 common dates) and currently stable \u2014 monitor that pair for regression.",
      "purpose_match is 1.0 only for 2546\u21941560 and 0.0 for all others; its contribution is almost a pair-specific bias term rather than a generalizable signal \u2014 if new vehicles with mixed purpose data are added, this weight may need reassessment.",
      "Temperature_similarity is near 1.0 for all pairs across all splits, providing minimal discriminative signal; keeping it at 0.10 is safe but contributes little \u2014 it remains as a hedge against future seasonal variation."
    ]
  },
